“A list is only as strong as its weakest link.” — Donald Knuth

Some terminology

A variety of definitions of the terms used here have been circulating around, so before we begin I would like to define some of them more formally for the sake of this writing.

microservice — an independent service managed by an individual or a group. It may differ between organizations, their team sizes, business processes etc. It is also referred to as service.

microservice architecture — a collection of micro-services that structures an application. Sometimes this is also referred to as microservices.

upstream service — the microservice we are receiving requests from.

downstream service — the microservice we are making requests to.

SLA — service level agreement. This is the agreement between service and client about measurable metrics e.g. availability, throughput, response time etc.

The problem

Imagine you have hundreds of teams, developing and maintaining hundreds of microservices. Imagine also that the system is handling thousands of requests per second and has strong SLAs. This forms a huge service call graph and a lot of performance and failure implications which have to be thought about in advance.

What is microservice resilience ?

Resilience means “the capacity to recover quickly from difficulties”. A resilient microservice should be able to self-heal and recover after some reasonable time and this implies recovering from both software and hardware failures.

In order to have resilience some prerequisites have to be met. First of all we need well defined SLAs. These define the contract on a variety of metrics and agreements between the parties in the system. Next we need to have all the use cases in our microservice. We should be able to quickly identify and document the possible failure points which is difficult without the use cases. And last but not least we must have observability. This includes health and deep checks, application metrics, logging, dashboards etc. Not only would this help us identify eventual failures but would give us a view on how to improve the system.

“You can’t improve what you don’t measure.” — Jacob Drucker

Therefore to have a resilient microservice it must be observable, self-healing and fault tolerant in the microservice environment it lives. The latter is what we will dive into until the end of this writing.

Fault tolerance patterns and Resilence4j

Fault tolerance is the ability of a system to continue functioning in the event of a failure although the overall performance may suffer. There are a number of well known fault tolerance patterns we will dive into and describe here.

“Resilience4j is a lightweight, easy-to-use fault tolerance library inspired by Netflix Hystrix, but designed for Java 8 and functional programming…
It provides higher-order functions (decorators) to enhance any functional interface, lambda expression or method reference…
You can stack more than one decorator on any functional interface, lambda expression or method reference…
With Resilience4j you don’t have to go all-in, you can pick what you need.”
— https://resilience4j.readme.io/docs

Most of the modules in Resilience4j have blocking and non-blocking APIs and have common configuration to ignore or accept specific exceptions and decide on a failure.

Retry

As its name suggests the Retry pattern refers to retrying the logic on designated operations. A typical example is a request being retried until successful. However there are some pitfalls. A larger amount of retries can make things even worse or even prevent the service or the downstream service from recovering. A request retry in a distributed system can trigger multiple other requests or retries and start a cascading effect in other applications.

Imagine receiving a request from an upstream service which triggers 20 requests in our downstream services, then retrying 1 request a 1000 times would trigger 20000 requests in the downstream services.

Although retrying looks like an easy approach it usually has to be implemented using a carefully chosen backoff strategy. A common approach is to use an exponentially increasing wait time up until a maximum retry count has been reached.

Resilience4J — Retry

RetryConfig config = RetryConfig.custom()
    .failAfterMaxAttempts(true)
    .waitDuration(Duration.ofSeconds(1))
    .intervalFunction(integer -> 2L * integer)
    .maxAttempts(3)
    .build();Retry retry = RetryRegistry.of(config).retry("downstream:/api/foo");retry.executeRunnable(() -> {
  // retry logic here
});

In this example we have defined a retry logic with 3 attempts doubling the wait duration after each failure starting with a wait duration of 1 second.

For more configuration properties of the Retry see: https://resilience4j.readme.io/docs/retry

Timeout

A timeout is another commonly used pattern and it is already supported by most clients (tcp, http, database etc). Although it seems trivial there are a number of decisions to be made when configuring timeout. First of all we want our timeouts to be high enough to allow slower requests to succeed but low enough to stop waiting for a request that is never going to succeed. Secondly we should avoid unbounded waiting times for responses and thus treating every request as failed when no response was received within the timeout. And last but not least we need to have a fallback mechanism for when the request timed out in the client but was successful on the server.

Resilience4j — Timelimiter

The module of Resilience4j that deals with timeouts is called Timelimiter. The only configuration is has is the timeout duration.

TimeLimiterConfig config = TimeLimiterConfig.custom()
    .timeoutDuration(Duration.ofSeconds(1))
    .build();

TimeLimiter timeLimiter = TimeLimiterRegistry.of(config)
    .timeLimiter("slow-response-timeouts");

timeLimiter.executeFutureSupplier(
    () -> CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> "Hello world!"));

More about Timelimiter here: https://resilience4j.readme.io/docs/retry

Rate Limiter

Rate Limiter helps us protect the server from over loading by limiting the number of calls we could make/process in a specific window. It could also protect our downstream services from overloading with requests. In case we limit the number of requests in our service we later need to do either of the following:

  • retry at a later time the “limited” requests
  • go with some default/cached values for the responses
  • just throw away requests and do not return successful responses

Very often rate limiters are used to flatten the curve and smooth out bursts of request during traffic peaks.

Imagine there is a service responsible for fetching 100 stock prices which talks to a 3rd party service. Stock prices are updated once in every 5 seconds and we get 100 req/s per stock price. Should we really make those calls to the 3rd party service?

Resilience4j — Ratelimiter

The ratelimiter module of Resilience4j is highly configurable and at the same time — easy to use.

RateLimiterConfig config = RateLimiterConfig.custom()
    .timeoutDuration(Duration.ofMillis(5L))
    .limitRefreshPeriod(Duration.ofSeconds(1))
    .limitForPeriod(200)
    .build();

RateLimiter rateLimiter = RateLimiterRegistry.of(config)
    .rateLimiter("peak-traffic-limiter");

rateLimiter.executeCallable(() -> "Hello world!");

The configuration properties in the above example are:

  • timeout duration — the default wait for permission duration after which the execution fails.
  • limit for period — the number of executions representing the actual rate of the rate limiter.
  • limit refresh period — represents a period when the rate limiter sets its permissions count to limitForPeriod value.

In the example above we have a rate limiter configuration with a maximum of 200 operations per second waiting 5 milliseconds until one fails.

For more information see: https://resilience4j.readme.io/docs/ratelimiter

Circuit Breaker

As the name suggests it acts just as an electrical circuit breaker. When the number of consecutive failures crosses a threshold, the circuit breaker opens, and for the duration of a timeout period all attempts to invoke the remote service will fail immediately.

“In electronics, a circuit breaker is a switch that protects your components from damage through overload. In software, a circuit breaker protects your services from being spammed while already being partly unavailable due to high load.”

An interesting property of the circuit breaker is that it has three states — Closed, Open, Half-open.

  • Closed — requests can flow freely
  • Open — requests are rejected without being submitted to the remote resource
  • Half-open — one probe request is allowed to decide whether to close the circuit again

Resilience4j — Circuitbreaker

There could be much more configurations, so we will not go into too much details.

CircuitBreakerConfig circuitBreakerConfig = CircuitBreakerConfig
    .custom()
    .slidingWindowType(COUNT_BASED)
    .slidingWindowSize(10)
    .failureRateThreshold(75.0f)
    .waitDurationInOpenState(Duration.ofSeconds(3))
    .permittedNumberOfCallsInHalfOpenState(2)
    .build();

CircuitBreaker circuitBreaker = CircuitBreaker.of(
    "too-many-failures-breaker", 
    circuitBreakerConfig
);circuitBreaker.transitionToClosedState();

circuitBreaker.decorateSupplier(() -> "Hello world!").get();

The configuration above defines a count based circuit breaker (as opposed to a time based one) with a sliding window of 10 requests and a failure rate threshold of 75%. The circuit breaker will open if 75% of the requests start to fail of the sliding window of 10 requests — 8 failures in this case. If we used a TIME_BASED window size then the sliding window is in seconds.

For more information see: https://resilience4j.readme.io/docs/circuitbreaker

Rate Limiter VS Circuit Breaker

Although these two look very similar they are semantically different.

  • A Rate Limiter prevents ourselves from overloading by controlling throughput.
  • A Circuit Breaker prevents the downstream service from overloading in case it starts failing or becomes unresponsive.

Bulkhead

The bulkhead pattern helps us avoid faults in one part of the system to take the entire system down. The name comes from ships where a bulkhead is a wall within the hull of a ship which prevents the entire ship from sinking if that partition is flooded.

The name comes from ships where a bulkhead is a wall within the hull of a ship which prevents the entire ship from sinking if that partition is flooded. Failure in one service or a group of services should not bring down the whole application.

The bulkhead pattern helps us allocate limit on the resources which can be used for specific services so that resource exhaustion can be reduced. For example it could be used to separate downstream service calls, database calls etc. in which case if one downstream service fails that would not affect our service from calling the others.

Resilience4j — Bulkhead

The bulkhead implementation in Resilience4j supports a semaphore and a thread pool based bulkhead.

Semaphore based

BulkheadConfig config = BulkheadConfig.custom()
    .fairCallHandlingStrategyEnabled(true)
    .maxConcurrentCalls(10)
    .maxWaitDuration(Duration.ofMillis(100L))
    .build();

Bulkhead bulkhead = BulkheadRegistry.ofDefaults().bulkhead("semaphore-based", config);

bulkhead.executeCallable(() -> "Hello world!");
  • maxConcurrentCalls — amount of parallel executions allowed by the bulkhead.
  • maxWaitDuration — amount of time a thread should be blocked for when attempting to enter a saturated bulkhead.

ThreadPool based

ThreadPoolBulkheadConfig config = ThreadPoolBulkheadConfig.custom()
    .maxThreadPoolSize(10)
    .coreThreadPoolSize(5)
    .queueCapacity(100)
    .keepAliveDuration(Duration.ofSeconds(1))
    .build();

ThreadPoolBulkhead bulkhead = ThreadPoolBulkheadRegistry.of(config).bulkhead("thread-based");

bulkhead.executeCallable(() -> "Hello world!");
  • maxThreadPoolSize , coreThreadPoolSize, queueCapacity — these are pretty self explanatory and define the properties of the underlying thread pool.
  • keepAliveDuration — maximum time that excess idle threads will wait for new tasks before terminating.

Maintaining a number of bulkheads gives us the opportunity to divide executions.

For more see: https://resilience4j.readme.io/docs/bulkhead

Cache

Caching is another fault tolerance pattern which is widely used. It’s a huge topic and is here for the sake of completeness. The idea is to save the data that comes from remote services to a local or remote cache and reuse the cached data as a response during downstream service failure.

We’ll briefly summarise that there are lot of decisions to be made when designing a cache:

  • type of cache (in-memory, local storage, distributed etc.) — the choice depends on the use case and cache size wanted.
  • caching strategies — write-through and cache-aside.
  • write policies — pre-caching or on-demand caching.
  • replacement strategies — usually based on a predefined cache size although sometimes caches could be unlimited.
  • cache invalidation strategy — based on time or freshness or activity.

“There are only two hard things in Computer Science: cache invalidation and naming things.” — Phil Karlton

Resilience4j — Cache

It uses the Java Temporary Caching API which supports a variety of caches — Ehcache, Caffeine, Redisson, Hazelcast, Ignite.

CacheManager cacheManager = Caching.getCachingProvider().getCacheManager();

Cache<String, String> cache = Cache.of(cacheManager.createCache("my-cache", new MutableConfiguration<>()));

Cache.decorateSupplier(cache, () -> "Hello world!").apply("hello-key");

For more details see: https://resilience4j.readme.io/docs/cache and https://jcp.org/aboutJava/communityprocess/implementations/jsr107/index.html

Asynchronous Processing

When we talk about fault tolerance we should also mention the asynchronous processing. Again, this is huge and is here for entirety. The idea is that any message can be sent independently of the availability of the receiver meaning that the messages will get delivered as soon as the service becomes available. Therefore this also provides natural redelivery and retry mechanisms. Just like a rate limiter it helps smooth out traffic bursts and the downstream service cloud process the messages an approximately average rate. However it could be quite difficult to implement if we want to mimic an HTTP call. HTTP uses a request-response paradigm which makes it duplex. When using queues we have to consider an inbound and an outbound queue in case we need the responses. If we have multiple APIs in a service, this could easily lead to unbearable complexity.

Implementing asynchronous processing can be achieved using:

  • Client/Server in-memory queues
  • Distributed messaging brokers e.g. RabbitMQ, Kafka etc.

In its nature Resilience4j is asynchronous and provides in-memory queueing mechanisms in most of its modules. A more robust approach however would be to use an external distributed messaging broker.

Some key points

  • If a service SLA is 100rps and is now degraded to 50rps it won’t do 100rps no matter how hard we brute force it, so if we have an ill service let if self-heal.
  • A degradation in one service could cause partial failures in other services which could cascade to a full system failure.
  • Setting up a distributed system for fault tolerance is not a trivial task and consists of the following steps:
    - Define service SLAs
    - Tweak microservice calls with fault tolerance in mind
    - Observe the system
    - Go back to redefining the SLAs
